<body>

<div1 type="letter">

<pb facs="nei.j4a.2.39-40_0002" />

<fw type="curatorial">40</fw>

<fw type="letterhead">
The Outlook
<lb/>
 287 Fourth Avenue
<lb/>
New York
<lb/>

Editorial Rooms</fw>

<opener>
<dateline>October 15, 1912</dateline>



<salute>My dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
</opener>
<p>Thank you very much for your kind note. You probably saw what I said about your recent volume in an earlier number of <title>The Outlook</title>. I meant to send it to you, but I am not sure that it ever got to you.</p>

<p>I really think greatly of your work; the fineness and the elevation of it, as well as the freshness and force of it. I have been meaning to write you with my own hand; but I am planning to leave for Japan three weeks from to-day<sic>today</sic>, and I have a been overwhelmed with work of all kinds.</p>
<closer>
<salute>With all sorts of good wishes</salute>
<salute>Faithfully yours,</salute>

<signed>Hamilton W. Mabie</signed>

</closer>

<note>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</note>
  
<pb facs="nei.j4a.2.39-40_0001"/>

   <fw type="curatorial">39</fw>

<note type="recipient">Mabie, famous <unclear>into</unclear> of his day</note>

</div1>
